00:49:29.770 --> 00:49:32.540
Yeah, and I detail some
of this more in the book.

00:49:32.540 --> 00:49:35.140
I won't go into all
of it here, but not

00:49:35.140 --> 00:49:37.960
all of the terms of
the Geneva Conventions

00:49:37.960 --> 00:49:42.550
apply to conflicts which are not
of an international character,

00:49:42.550 --> 00:49:45.587
so there's some slippage
there to decide,

00:49:45.587 --> 00:49:47.170
for example, in the
case of the Balkan

00:49:47.170 --> 00:49:50.620
Wars in the 1980s
and early 1990s,

00:49:50.620 --> 00:49:55.150
the debate was between whether
to call the war in Yugoslavia

00:49:55.150 --> 00:49:57.280
a non-international armed
conflict taking place

00:49:57.280 --> 00:49:59.464
within the boundaries
of a single state,

00:49:59.464 --> 00:50:00.880
and then also the
question, did it

00:50:00.880 --> 00:50:02.530
turn into an
international conflict

00:50:02.530 --> 00:50:04.870
after say Serbia broke off?

00:50:04.870 --> 00:50:06.580
Because that would determine--

00:50:06.580 --> 00:50:09.650
that determined at that
point, for example,

00:50:09.650 --> 00:50:14.080
which leaders might ultimately
be tried for war crimes, what

00:50:14.080 --> 00:50:16.210
kind of intelligence
gathering or information

00:50:16.210 --> 00:50:18.250
gathering might take
place during the conflict

00:50:18.250 --> 00:50:22.180
itself to be used subsequently
for retrospective prosecutions,

00:50:22.180 --> 00:50:25.050
so that boundary between
international and

00:50:25.050 --> 00:50:27.580
non-international was
operative in those wars.

00:50:27.580 --> 00:50:30.510
In later conflicts,
like Syria for instance,

00:50:30.510 --> 00:50:33.400
it has implications first
for the basic question--

00:50:33.400 --> 00:50:36.840
is this a police action
by a legitimate regime,

00:50:36.840 --> 00:50:39.750
like the Assad regime
and other countries

00:50:39.750 --> 00:50:42.030
should stay far away from that?

00:50:42.030 --> 00:50:45.780
If it is determined,
as in the case of Syria

00:50:45.780 --> 00:50:48.570
by the ICRC that
this is, in fact,

00:50:48.570 --> 00:50:51.930
a non-international armed
conflict under Protocol Two

00:50:51.930 --> 00:50:55.440
of the Geneva Conventions,
then various other things

00:50:55.440 --> 00:50:58.770
kick in, like the ability
to take humanitarian aid in.

00:50:58.770 --> 00:51:02.730
Also again to gather information
for potential prosecutions

00:51:02.730 --> 00:51:03.730
later on.

00:51:03.730 --> 00:51:06.360
So there are those different--
two sets of boundaries.

00:51:06.360 --> 00:51:08.580
One between non-international
and international armed

00:51:08.580 --> 00:51:11.310
conflicts which determine which
parts of the Geneva Conventions

00:51:11.310 --> 00:51:13.410
take place, and then
the broader debate

00:51:13.410 --> 00:51:16.620
about whether it's
an armed conflict

00:51:16.620 --> 00:51:19.530
in this international
legal sense at all.

00:51:19.530 --> 00:51:22.710
If not, if it's an insurrection
or rebellion, for instance--

00:51:22.710 --> 00:51:24.750
that's something
which is usually

00:51:24.750 --> 00:51:30.000
determined to take place under
the rule of domestic law.

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:34.350
There may be some possibilities
for human rights violations

00:51:34.350 --> 00:51:37.020
to be used in later
prosecutions there,

00:51:37.020 --> 00:51:39.730
but it's not under the
international humanitarian law,

00:51:39.730 --> 00:51:41.620
necessarily so it's--

00:51:41.620 --> 00:51:44.100
drawing those boundaries
becomes very important in terms

00:51:44.100 --> 00:51:46.440
of what kind of relief
can be brought in,

00:51:46.440 --> 00:51:48.500
what sort of
[? posterior ?] political

00:51:48.500 --> 00:51:53.460
or military outside powers will
take towards the conflict, what

00:51:53.460 --> 00:51:56.640
the legal consequences may be
for those who are prosecuting

00:51:56.640 --> 00:52:00.900
it, if at the end
of the conflict

00:52:00.900 --> 00:52:03.625
you get war crimes
trials, for instance.

00:52:03.625 --> 00:52:05.250
So there's a whole
host of implications

00:52:05.250 --> 00:52:08.520
that flow from that, and I think
that determines the reluctance

00:52:08.520 --> 00:52:11.070
of organizations
like the ICRC to make

00:52:11.070 --> 00:52:14.272
that decision about
whether this is

00:52:14.272 --> 00:52:15.730
a non-international
armed conflict,

00:52:15.730 --> 00:52:18.450
because from that
will flow a host

00:52:18.450 --> 00:52:21.240
of other legal and
political consequences

00:52:21.240 --> 00:52:24.810
as well, which have to be taken
into account during the course

00:52:24.810 --> 00:52:26.887
of the conflict and also
subsequently as well.

00:52:26.887 --> 00:52:29.220
Something that's observable--
I didn't mention this just

00:52:29.220 --> 00:52:30.750
because of time, but--

00:52:30.750 --> 00:52:34.020
is the way in which
non-international armed

00:52:34.020 --> 00:52:42.270
conflicts, civil wars, are
actually becoming more and more

00:52:42.270 --> 00:52:45.060
conducted under international
humanitarian law,

00:52:45.060 --> 00:52:48.270
because those who might
be thought of by others

00:52:48.270 --> 00:52:52.920
as insurgents or rebels are
very keen, for obvious reasons,

00:52:52.920 --> 00:52:56.040
to get the recognition of
the international community,

00:52:56.040 --> 00:53:01.380
to have the regularization
of warfare itself,

00:53:01.380 --> 00:53:04.110
to give them recognition
as legitimate belligerents

00:53:04.110 --> 00:53:06.030
within those conflicts.

00:53:06.030 --> 00:53:08.280
That gives them a
military and political

00:53:08.280 --> 00:53:13.380
and even an ethical advantage
in those conflicts as well.

00:53:13.380 --> 00:53:17.790
So we're actually seeing now at
the moment in the 21st century,

00:53:17.790 --> 00:53:20.890
greater usage of
international humanitarian law

00:53:20.890 --> 00:53:24.450
in civil conflicts than had
been the-- internal conflicts

00:53:24.450 --> 00:53:26.640
than had been the case
in inter-state war,

00:53:26.640 --> 00:53:28.870
partly for empirical reasons.

00:53:28.870 --> 00:53:30.660
Most of the wars
going on are indeed

00:53:30.660 --> 00:53:33.150
those non-international
armed conflicts,

00:53:33.150 --> 00:53:36.810
but also because there are
greater rewards for competence

00:53:36.810 --> 00:53:40.187
to comply with international
humanitarian law

00:53:40.187 --> 00:53:41.520
during those conflicts, as well.

00:53:41.520 --> 00:53:45.990
It's also the case
that more and more

00:53:45.990 --> 00:53:49.140
internal non-international
civil wars are being concluded

00:53:49.140 --> 00:53:52.530
by treaties now than any
other form of conflict,

00:53:52.530 --> 00:53:55.020
because that provides
a means for negotiating

00:53:55.020 --> 00:53:59.700
among the parties, for
clearing up some of the debates

00:53:59.700 --> 00:54:01.840
and disputes about conduct
during the conflicts

00:54:01.840 --> 00:54:02.640
themselves.

00:54:02.640 --> 00:54:04.950
Also for bringing in the
international community

00:54:04.950 --> 00:54:09.610
as brokers or arbitrators,
and guarantors

00:54:09.610 --> 00:54:13.170
of those international-- those
agreements among the parties

00:54:13.170 --> 00:54:14.470
as well.

00:54:14.470 --> 00:54:18.300
So in a paradoxical
way, civil war

00:54:18.300 --> 00:54:20.940
is on the leading edge of
international humanitarian law

00:54:20.940 --> 00:54:23.790
and the civilization of
warfare more generally.

00:54:23.790 --> 00:54:25.920
So again, a great
deal hangs not just

00:54:25.920 --> 00:54:27.900
for individual
specific conflict,

00:54:27.900 --> 00:54:30.390
but also for the
future of conflict

00:54:30.390 --> 00:54:33.410
as a whole being
driven by civil war

00:54:33.410 --> 00:54:36.240
and the international armed
conflict through its pressures

00:54:36.240 --> 00:54:39.060
on international
humanitarian law right now.

00:54:39.060 --> 00:54:39.810
Thank you so much.

00:54:39.810 --> 00:54:41.101
Thanks for the great questions.

00:54:41.101 --> 00:54:43.160
[APPLAUSE]

